ra>His wife Hajah Fauziah Alias, 63, was among several passengers who were hospitalised.</Para><Para>Haji Abu Bakar's niece Amilia Gani heard the news when she was at work on Tuesday evening.</Para><Para>Her mother Amlah Osman is Haji Abu Bakar's older sister.</Para><Para>"It was not easy because we had to pull together our family members to console my mother and try to find out more information," said the 47-year-old. "It was very sudden. We are all very devastated."</Para><Para>Ms Amilia described her uncle as loving. "He was very wise with his words and consoled me through many troubling times," she said, adding that he often did charitable work for religious causes with her mother.</Para><Para>Haji Abu Bakar's granddaughter, who wanted to be identified only as Ms Aishah, said he had always been concerned about his family's religious education.</Para><Para>"He would teach his children and grandchildren about our culture and religion," said the 21-year-old.</Para><Para>Ms Amilia added that her uncle would organise weekly prayer sessions for the Muslim community in his office.</Para><Para>Haji Abu Bakar's three children left Singapore for Saudi Arabia on Wednesday for the burial.</Para><Para>His wife was warded in the intensive care unit of King Faisal Hospital with two other passengers.</Para><Para>Ten others were reported on Tuesday to be at another hospital, while 17 have been discharged.</Para><Para>No update on the condition of the injured was available.</Para><Para>A spokesman for Abu Bakar Travel Services said it has been organising pilgrimages - about two or three times a year - since it began operations in 2002, and that it regularly charters buses from the bus operator involved in Tuesday's incident. This was the first accident it has encountered, he added.</Para><Para>The spokesman said that a private prayer session for family, friends and employees of Haji Abu Bakar was held yesterday evening.</Para><Para>In a post on its Facebook page, Abu Bakar Travel Services thanked well-wishers for their condolences on the death of its director.</Para><Para>"Together we pray for the well-being and recovery of Hajah Fauziah Alias and all the other pilgrims," the agency said.</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">Kimberley Chia,Zhaki Abdullah </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field">Haji Abu Bakar Osman was killed when the bus he was travelling in crashed in Mecca on Tuesday. </Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">(c) 2018 Singapore Press Holdings Limited </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

